Having said all that, the primaries are known for their volatility and unpredictability therefore this is something I've factored into my forecast.

Over the past several weeks Sanders has gained in Iowa and is now slightly ahead in the polls. Historically he has outperformed his poll numbers since he brings in Independents, Republicans, and low-propensity voters that polling firms tend to miss, since they target democratic voters who have voted in the last 2 presidential primaries.

I'm making a slight adjustment to this forecast. According to FiveThirtyEight (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-primary-forecast/iowa/), Sanders is forecasted to beat Biden by a slight margin. I do not assess it is enough to put Sanders above Biden yet, given Biden being the front runner since early Dec '19.

Multiple polls remain close and the % of voters who have made up their mind appears to remain around the 50% mark. This creates quite a bit of uncertainty who will come out on top. Biden has a slim lead in some polls, but Sanders appears to be on the rise probably based on support for his health care proposals (key issue). Warren remains the 2nd choice for many voters and could become a wildcard once the caucuses refine the list to viable candidates.

While Klobuchar has been polling well in Iowa, her and any of the other candidates not listed here have consistently polled with unwinnable numbers since the start of their campaign. That is statistically unlikely to change dramatically or to be wrong.

Biden has held the lead in the polls; however, Sanders is surging (and may have the current lead according to some current polls). In 2016, Sanders surged late as well where his economic message seemed to resonate. Given that Sanders has stayed fairly consistent, there are no indicators that this primary will be that much different from 2016 where Sanders and Clinton were extremely close. Biden will most likely win in the less rural areas/cities in Iowa, and Sanders will maintain a strong base in the more rural counties.

I would like Bernie to win, but I will put that aside. He has a strong chance, but Biden is the safe bet, and the older generation will get out to vote as they always do. Popular media consumed by this huge part of the population will sway them towards Biden. Bernie support is most vocal and shows more than will turn out.
Bernie surging, plus the experience of 2016 in caucuses is that his supporters can be rather persuasive, which earns him a bit of a bump.

I read today a phrase that I think sums Biden's candidacy up nicely. Someone somewhere (can't remember where) said, "Biden is a stand-in for 'none of the above'." I think that's true; and it isn't like "none of the above" can't get the most votes, but "none of the above" rarely has the most enthusiastic support.

The polls show that Biden, Sanders, Warren and Buttigieg are all extremely close together. Biden is currently in front but not much in front of Sanders.[1] Klobuchar has been climbing in the polls as well recently and could potentially make the 15% threshold.

At the moment, both Biden and Buttigieg have a physical presence in Iowa while Sanders and Warren are occupied by the impeachment trial. Sanders and Warren are competing for similar voter populations, which is splitting their vote. In addition, both Buttigieg and Biden have seen spikes in popularity lately, yet Biden has been consistently positioning himself as the moderate candidate who can beat Trump.
Impeachment trial is throwing a monkey wrench into the caucus

Biden has the lead in a more conservative state and with his brand name. Bernie shows no signs of slowing down; Warren has been sliding in polls and likeability recently, notably picking a fight with Sanders over sexism. Pete has an outside shot being a midwesterner, but has not been effective recently (his resume is much stronger than his recent performance). I'd put my money on Pete being #2 with moderate split 66/33 between Warren and Biden, Sanders splitting lefties 80/20 with Warren. Klobuchar is the only other candidate who might be able to sneak in to the top 3.

This is due to a combination of factors, I have updated to the latest polling averages on 538 and reduced the error rather arbitrarily to 8% points as the caucus gets closer. I have also updated the second preferences of voters who are not voting for any of the main candidates according to https://www.focusonruralamerica.com/2020/01/20/january-poll-results/ which makes a big difference as I previously assumed they would split equally between the candidates and this survey in particular shows that they have very low polling for Sanders among this group. This in turn makes it hard for Sanders to pick up the necessary delegates to win an overall majority. However my current model doesn't allow for errors of the second preference polling, so this should come with a pinch of salt until I've fixed that.

In past years Iowa has been quite important and predictive of who was going to be the eventual Democratic Party nominee (while being less predictive on the Republican side). This has a good chance of changing this year because we're going to have 4, possibly 5 candidates emerge out of Iowa with double-digit showings. Unless someone emerges in the next few weeks with a clear lead and Kerry '04, Obama '08-margin it won't mean much by March other than expectations met or not met. Traditionally there have been 3 tickets out of Iowa, we may have as many as 5 this time. Two major polling aggregators show this (once accounting for MoE), at: https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/ia/iowa_democratic_presidential_caucus-6731.html AND https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/election-update-the-first-post-debate-polls-are-in-and-theyre-pretty-weird/

Karl Rove May be many things but he does know polls... the crowd forecast seems to reflect tight race as well. “While it’s unlikely there will be major changes in public opinion before the Iowa caucuses, the race is so closely bunched that even small changes could produce a much different outcome than polls suggest today. There are two reasons. First, Iowans take seriously their participation in the country’s first contest. Both Selzer and Monmouth find around 40% have firmly made up their minds, but 45% in the Selzer poll say they “could be persuaded” and 13% haven’t made a choice. The comparable Monmouth numbers are 52% still “open” and 5% with no choice yet. Second, Iowa Democratic Party rules say that if a caucus participant’s preferred candidate doesn’t receive 15% of the vote in the attendee’s precinct, then he must chose another candidate or head home to await final results. Selzer finds 32% undecided or supporting candidates with less than 15% total support; Monmouth has around 26%. These voters’ second-choice preferences are likely to be especially important. The two recent polls provide conflicting guidance as to where these people will break when their candidates lose. Selzer says Ms. Warren gets 16% as a second choice, Mr. Buttigieg 15% and Messrs. Biden and Sanders 12% each. Monmouth finds that 23% pick Ms. Warren as their second choice, vaulting her to first place. Fifteen percent say Mr. Buttigieg is their second choice, 14% pick Mr. Sanders and only 10% choose Mr. Biden, the same percentage who would turn to Ms. Klobuchar. How this plays out depends on which candidates lack 15% in which of the state’s 1,681 precincts and what the field above them looks like in each meeting place. No candidate’s support will be consistent across the state. Iowa used to punch the tickets of three candidates to proceed. This year, winners and losers in Iowa will be judged more by how they meet expectations than by vote percentage. The most likely outcome is that Ms. Warren and Messrs. Biden, Sanders and Buttigieg split Iowa’s 41 delegates roughly equally, with Ms. Klobuchar perhaps grabbing a couple. The Democratic presidential race is as up for grabs at this point as any in modern U.S. electoral history. That means buckle up: There are lots of surprises and plenty of turmoil ahead.“ https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-four-way-race-for-iowa-11579133565

I think Warren made a mistake starting the flap with Sanders, and that CNN's effectively taking Warren's side has backfired to the advantage of Sanders. My intuition is based primarily on the jaw-dropping bias of the moderator last night, who rejected Sanders' denial that he had said that a woman couldn't get elected. I think this feeds into the - somewhat justified - perception by Sanders' supporters that he can't get a fair shake from the press or the Democratic Party. So I think the whole controversy subtracts Warren voters and adds them to Sanders' total.

Current polling gives Elizabeth Warren about 15% of the vote and the other big three 20% each. However, in previous such votes, voters switched their vote from their preferred candidate to their least-disliked/next best candidate, when their preferred candidate wasn't likely to win. Hence I expect Elizabeth Warren's vote share to fall and the other three to rise, as her supporters decide she won't win and thus vote for someone else. This is further backed up by her funding falling recently, indicating that her campaign is stalling.

Pete has the most enthusiastic supporters and Joe has the dependable, always voting older voters. I believe that the enthusiasm of Petes supporters will outweigh the traditional voters. Also there may be some strategic voting by Warren and Sanders voters who want to keep Biden from winning when possible and may see a vote for Pete as more important than a vote for their preference, Warren and Sanders, even if he is not their first choice.
